From 53e0fb328470f72dca677c17e899a3317b7365a1 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Chronium Build <chronium@interlink.local>
Date: Mon, 8 Jun 2026 08:41:24 +0700
Subject: [PATCH 09/14] chronium: per-profile navigator.languages +
 Element.getBoundingClientRect sub-pixel noise

Two surfaces in one patch; both share the FingerprintState plumbing.

navigator.languages / navigator.language
  Reads the profile JSON's 'languages' array (or falls back to
  accept_language string) and carries it to renderers via the new
  kFingerprintAcceptLanguage switch. NavigatorLanguage's
  EnsureUpdatedLanguage now checks FingerprintState first, before
  the DevTools probe::ApplyAcceptLanguageOverride path, so the
  override wins for both worker and document contexts.

  Verified: profile B JSON 'languages: [vi-VN, vi, en-US, en]'
  -> navigator.language === 'vi-VN',
  navigator.languages === ['vi-VN','vi','en-US','en'].

Element.getBoundingClientRect sub-pixel noise
  Adds a seeded ~1e-5 magnitude perturbation to each of x/y/width/
  height. KEY DESIGN POINT: the noise is applied on the DOMRect
  (double precision) AFTER conversion from gfx::RectF, NOT on the
  RectF itself. RectF's float32 relative epsilon (~1.2e-7) at typical
  layout magnitudes (200-1000 px) is ~3e-5, which would swallow our
  noise. DOMRect's double storage preserves it cleanly.

  Verified: r1.x = 272.99999880 (was 273.00000000 baseline),
  r1.width = 818.99999429, two calls return identical value
  (deterministic per profile).

  getClientRects() is left unpatched: still works on Vector<RectF>
  where the same float32 epsilon problem applies. Every common
  fingerprinter (creepjs, fingerprintjs, pixelscan) reads
  getBoundingClientRect, not getClientRects.

